Keeping the Secret of Genetic Testing
What is genetic risk ?
Genetic risk refers to your chance of inheriting a disorder or disease .
People get certain diseases because of genetic changes .
How much a genetic change tells us about your chance of developing a disorder is not always clear .
If your genetic results indicate that you have gene changes associated with an increased risk of heart disease , it does not mean that you definitely will develop heart disease .
The opposite is also true .
If your genetic results show that you do not have changes associated with an increased risk of heart disease , it is still possible that you will develop heart disease .
However , for some rare diseases , people who have certain gene changes are guaranteed to develop the disease .
When we are diagnosed with certain genetic diseases , are we supposed to disclose this result to our relatives ?
My answer is no .
On one hand , we do not want this potential danger causing frightening effects in our families ' lives .
When people around us know that we have a certain disease , their behavior will change , whether caring for us too much or keeping away from us .
And both are not what we want , since most of us just want to live as normal people .
Surrounded by such concerns , it is very likely that we would be distracted to worry about these problems .
It is a concern that would be with us during our whole life , because we would never know when the '' potential bomb '' would explode .
On the other hand , if there were ways that could help us to control or cure the disease , we could go through this process with the help of the whole family .
For example , if exercising is helpful for a potential family disease , we could always look for more chances for the family to exercise together .
And we could keep track of all family members ' health conditions .
At the same time , we would be prepared if we learned that other family members got this disease .
Here I want to share Forest 's view on this issue .
Although some people feel that an individual who is found to carry a dominant gene for Huntington 's disease has an ethical obligation to disclose that fact to his or her siblings , there currently is no legal requirement to do so .
In fact , requiring someone to communicate his or her own genetic risk to family members who are therefore also at risk is considered by many to be ethically dubious .
"
Nothing is absolutely right or wrong .
If a genetic test for a certain disease is very accurate , and it is unavoidable and necessary to get treatment that will be known to others , then it is okay to disclose the result .
Above all , life is more important than secrets .
Genetic risk has consequences that should not be taken lightly within a family circle .
Family members have a common genetic make up , shared by either of the parents , but what affects one family member may or may not affect another .
In cases where an individual has learned of a genetic disorder , disclosing this to his or her relatives is solely a matter of the individual 's own moral system .
The " right to know " issue is highly debatable ; although there may be a genetic risk , one can not be entirely sure it applies to all of one 's relatives , because the genetic information could have come from the families of either parent .
This also means that as soon as a person is made aware of his or her genetic profile , he or she gains knowledge about others ' .
This knowledge may be relevant to them .
An example that may serve as an illustration is breast cancer .
It is hereditary .
Should one who suffers from this disease keep it a secret from their relatives ?
It is also one 's duty to ensure that he or she undergo periodic healthchecks on one 's own .
Sometimes family structure and cultural beliefs can influence the pattern of communication .
In some families , the parents who learn of a son or daughter 's genetic risk would decide who is " allowed " to tell .
In many families , parents are seen as having the primary responsibility to pass on information to any offspring , regardless of who had first received information about genetic risk .
In addition , a woman testing positive for BRCA1 would be expected to allow her brother or sister to disclose such information to a niece or nephew , rather than do it herself ; however , this may be further complicated by an individual 's response to risk information , since they not want to know .
Hence , there were also tensions if participants felt that they could neither pass on information to relatives who needed to know ( such as nieces and nephews ) nor persuade those with authority ( the parents ) to do so .
The notion of authority also extended vertically .
For example , a grandmother may have more authority to pass on information than an aunt , even if the grandmother herself is not at risk and the aunt is .
These findings are important from a practitioner 's perspective , because patient constructs of the family and kinship may not be in line with geneticists ' views of family relationships , or about which blood ( or non-blood ) relatives should be informed and by whom ; these are also likely to be dependent on the cultural and ethnic context .
Ultimately , one must bring attention to who may benefit from such information , and to assist those at risk to make thoughtful decisions about disclosure .
Whose duty it is to inform at-risk relatives or not greatly depends on personal morals and the nature of how direct the risk is to them .
People with a close blood relationship generally carry some similar genes .
In such situations , if one of the family members or close relatives is found to carry a genetic risk , it is better for the patient to tell his or her close relatives about the issue and let others know about the risk . This way his or her family members can do some daily exercises to prevent the potential disease , or they may go to the hospital and check for the corresponding flaws .
In my opinion , although the announcement of carrying a genetic risk involves the issue of one 's privacy , the carrier should be obligated to inform his or her relatives in order for them to be able to take preventative measures against the potential disease .
I agree with this statement to a large extent .
I will focus on the negative side of sharing the genetic risk first .
Many patients with the genetic risk would want to keep it secret , because the genetic risk may indicate a high chance of carrying a certain disease .
Especially for young unmarried people , if they are known to have some genetic risk , there is a chance ( but not a certainty ) that their children would carry the same disease .
Therefore , keeping the information secret from her or her future spouse would help the relationship .
Secondly , announcing the potential risk would cause family members to be scared of this issue ; although the reaction would not be that serious , people would still fear that they would have some potential disease in the future , and thus go to the hospital and do additional checks or take more medicine in order to prevent the disease , creating unnecessary costs to the family .
Furthermore , the sharing the genetic risk would affect relationships with the relatives , because others may decide to keep their distance from the carrier , so as to lessen the chance of getting the potential disease .
On the other hand , while keeping the genetic risk secret may benefit the carrier to a certain extent and help to keep their privacy , it has much larger negative effects on the family members and relatives .
First , in the case of marriage , people should be honest and tell their spouse that they may carry certain genetic risks that may affect their offspring .
It is better to let the other party know than to wait until after the baby is born and a certain type of genetic disease is found .
It is better for both parties to be honest .
Secondly , genetic disease has a close relationship with one 's daily habits .
One example is when a person is told that he or she is at risk for diabetes .
In this case , the carrier can eat fewer candies and chocolates to lower their sugar intake ; at the same time , if the carrier shares this information with their relatives , they can perform the same exercise to consume less sugar and prevent the disease .
If the other parties did not know , they may end up with diabetes in the future , without having the chance to prevent it .
In conclusion , the benefits of sharing genetic risk with the carrier 's relatives outweighs the costs .
Therefore , it would be better for the carrier to be obligated to share the information with the relatives , in order to let them know and help prevent the potential disease through daily exercise .
Among diseases , a large number are caused by genetics .
A genetic disorder may or may not be a hereditary disease , and it is sometimes hard to find out whether one has these kinds of diseases .
A longstanding discussion is whether a carrier of a known genetic risk should be obligated to tell his or her relatives that his or her disease is caused by a gene .
From a legal aspect , the answer is no , but from an ethical aspect , the answer should be yes .
We can not make a law to push a carrier of a known genetic risk to tell his relatives about his genetic problem .
It is immoral and impractical .
Firstly , what diseases one has is a private matter .
And protection of one 's privacy is a human right .
A law should not require someone to tell others about their private matters , especially not against their will .
It is against his or her human rights , and it is against the spirit of the law .
The spirit of the law also includes fairness .
What is the basic difference between genetic disorders and other disorders ?
It is unfair to create a law singling out genetic disorders .
In addition , it is impractical to make such a law .
A good law should be clear and easy to execute .
However , there are many problems with enforcing a law requiring a carrier to tell his or her relatives the cause of his or her diseases .
Firstly , which relatives should be told ?
For example , does the carrier only need to tell his or her direct relatives , like parents and brothers and sisters , or does he also need to tell relatives like his grandmother 's sister 's son 's daughter 's nephew ?
Singling out the former is unfair .
Other relatives may have the same probability of developing such a disease .
How can a law exempt such a group of people from information needed to face their potential disease ?
However , there is also the ethical point of view .
A carrier should have a feeling of responsibility to tell his or her relatives of their genetic disorder .
By doing this , they may be able to save the lives of some of their relatives .
This is possible because a carrier with a bad gene may not necessarily acquire a genetic disease ; a healthy lifestyle may be able to mitigate the risk .
A typical example is genetically-caused hypertension .
Hypertension can be caused by genetic problems which make it more difficult for the carrier to process the fat and salt in their blood .
People usually get this kind of hypertension after they become adults .
However , if they already know they have a gene that puts them at higher risk for hypertension , they can develop a daily habit of avoiding salt and fat .

In a nutshell , our society can not require the carrier of a genetic risk to share their disease with their relatives , but such a carrier should be willing share that information .
By doing so , fewer of his or her loved ones will suffer from the genetic problem .
In the age of rapid technological advancement , a lot of medical breakthroughs are made possible .
One of these is genetic testing .
It is able to detect illnesses or diseases and even a child 's parentage .
However , it will become a controversial issue , because of the dilemma of whether a carrier of a known genetic risk must inform his or her relatives .
If the knowledge of the genetic risk were shared with the family or relatives , those relatives could take necessary precautions to prevent the disease .
But if the risk is for a terminal disease , some of the relatives may be disheartened upon learning about it .
Therefore , some carriers will prefer to keep it a secret .
This essay will discuss whether a carrier of a known genetic risk should tell his or her relatives .
Some believe that a person 's genetic risks should be kept secret because it is considered personal information .
Most patients will be depressed after realising his or her conditions .
If a test shows that a patient has a genetic disease , he or she might not wish to inform the relatives , since that may dishearten his extended family .
Some will wish to keep it to themselves in hopes of ensuring that they will not bring in any pessimism into their family .
Furthermore , some will wish not to become a burden to anyone , since seeking medical attention is relatively costly .
Hence , some see it as considerate to keep the genetic risk of getting a disease a confidential .
On the other hand , others may think that it would be considerate to tell the relatives , who will have a higher chance of sharing the genetic risk .
Hence , they would be able to seek help from medical specialists , to find a cure , or to take some measures to lower the risk of getting the disease .
In all cases , it will depend on what the genetic diseases are , as well as the current medical technology .
For example , breast cancer is a genetic disease that can be cured if it is discovered in its early stages .
With the knowledge this genetic risk , relatives of this genetic disease would have a medical check-up , which might save them by discovering it at an earlier stage .
In conclusion , it would be considerate to inform the relatives of their risk of getting the same genetic disease .
Although there might be a lot of challenges along the way in seeking medical attention , such as the financial issue , everyone should have the right to know their family 's inherited medical conditions .
However , some think that it might be better for them to remain ignorant about it so that they can continue leading a happy life .
In addition , some may think that even knowing about having a genetic risk for a disease will add to their misery because there is nothing that they can do about it .
In the end , it depends on the individual and also the nature of the disease , but an individual should be obligated to inform the relatives if there are possibilities of curing or preventing it .
Genetic testing is a personal decision , with the knowledge that there is a possibility that one could be a carrier or not .
Those who are born into a family with a history of genetic disease should be allowed to undergo genetic testing , even if there is no risk at all .
Early examination is healthy , because it will cast away unwanted doubts and affect the psychology of those who are affected .
For a genetic risk carrier , there should be choice given with regards to informing his or her relatives .
Carriers should not be forced or obliged to do so , as it may negatively and drastically affect the emotions of the genetic risk carrier .
There must be rules to regulate and exercise personal freedom regarding this choice .
If the genetic risk carrier is a minor , then the decision of informing the relatives should be made in consideration with the patient 's parents or legal guardians .
Such patients are still emotionally volatile , and they may be unaware of the consequences of their genetic disorder .
Furthermore , the act of informing others without the consent of their parents or the patient herself could harm the psychological state of the affected family .
Thus , much thought needs to be put on the immediate family , since it could cause a chain of unwanted events from the patient or the family members .
On learning of such a genetic disorder running in their family , some family members may feel hurt regarding their family pride or reputation .
However , there is a sense of responsibility to inform their relatives since it is a genetic disorder .
There might be a possibility that the genetic disorder could also affect their immediate relatives and any other family members within the same family tree .
The importance of informing relatives of a genetic disease is vital , because it may help to raise awareness and prevention of the genetic disorder .
Also , this known information will help their relatives to make informed decisions , and to similarly undergo genetic testing .
For example , the knowledge that a genetic disorder is benign would be beneficial .
And if the results turn out to be otherwise , then the family can be prepared emotionally and psychologically to aid the carrier in making decisions .
In addition , the genetic risk carrier would be showered with moral and emotional support from their relatives , if that knowledge were shared with them .
Having support from relatives is vital , because they can ensure the genetic risk carrier that he or she is not alone in facing their illness , and it will certainly provide a morale boost because the whole family will share a common sentiment towards the prospect of the genetic disorder , which could be inherited by anyone in the family .
Therefore , the decision to inform relatives of a genetic disorder will be dependent on the situation and the background of the affected family , with the liberty of choice given to the carrier in making the decision of informing others .
A person with a disorder , regardless of whether it is a mental or a physical disorder , is always easily known by his or her family .
When it comes to genetic issues , however , it is not that simple anymore .
Inheritance of genetic disorders moves from generation to generation , but not all children show the relevant symptoms .
Sometimes a family with a risk for a genetic disorder may not be able to detect the potential harm inside their bodies because none of their family members have any observable symptoms of the disorder .
Because of this , when one of the family members happens to feel uncomfortable or unhealthy , he or she should be told whether the disorder in his or her body is a genetic risk or not .
Afterward , the carrier will face a serious ethical issue , which is whether to reveal the problem to his or her relatives .
If the symptoms belong to a child , the parent will surely be informed by the medics , and the whole family will stay alert to their bodies ' condition .
On the contrary , if the carrier is an adult who may choose whether to inform his or her relatives about the risk , the situation will be more complex .
One may think that if the carrier is a caring person who loves his family more than himself , there is no doubt that he will tell his family about the issue .
That is true , and of course it is the obligation of a family member to protect and take care of his family .
Thought of another way , if a child of the family knows that he may be a genetic risk carrier , and the risk may be passed to his child in the future , his whole life will be a dilemma .
And of course , he or she will consider not having any children after getting married , and the same thought may occur to the cousins , as well .
As a result , the family tree ends the moment the adult carrier announces his issue .
In China , the older generation with a traditional culture background will always think of having more children as well as grandchildren , in order for the family to grow more strongly .
The reason for this is that after WWII , the population of China decreased dramatically , and so the government encouraged the people to have more children .
During that period , if one of the family members discovered symptoms of a genetic disorder , he would surely fall into an ethical dilemma .
Medical technology during that time was not advanced enough to completely cure him .
He had to choose whether to protect his family , or to make his family more prosperous , but with a potential genetic risk .
As a result , he would have chosen not to undergo genetic disorder testing , and let the truth be hidden forever .
This kind of ethical issue can not be judged by others , because they will not understand the position and the duty of the carrier in the family .
In conclusion , people should think carefully of the consequences of telling their relatives about their genetic disorders .
It is an obligation for a carrier to inform his relatives , but it is also an obligation for a family member to grow his family .
Regardless , if the disorder is rarely fatal , or if it does not cause any inconvenience to the carrier , revealing the truth is always the right thing to do .
In my opinion , the carrier should tell his or her relatives about it .
One of the reasons why is because as a carrier , he or she needs mental support to go through the situation .
It will be hard for an individual to deal with the issue on her own .
By telling his or her family , in addition to being a support , they could also possibly help her to get alternative solutions to the problem that she were facing .
In addition to that , I believe that the strong bond we have with our family is the biggest pillar of support to the carrier .
Furthermore , because it is a genetic problem , it will be better for the carrier to inform his or her family , because other family members might experience the same thing .
By making sure that they are aware of this genetic problem , they could have a full check-up for themselves , and thus they could even prevent it from happening to themselves .
I find that it is important to inform others especially when it is contagious , since the carrier could prevent the disease from spreading out to society .
For every action there are always pros and cons .
I believe that some carriers will choose not to reveal their disease to their family members because they do not want to make them worry or feel uncomfortable or even ostracized by them .
Furthermore , because treatment could require a lot of money , the carrier might not want to be a burden in her family .
I could understand the feeling of the carrier .
He or she does not want to be the source of unhappiness in the family .
However , we will never know ahead of time whether these negative effects will happen if the carrier decides to tell his or her family of his or her condition .
In conclusion , I believe that it is better for the carrier to inform her family members about the issue .
The carrier should be honest with his or her feelings , and I think that it is the right of the family members to know what is going on in his or her life .
If anything bad happened to the carrier without him or her having informed the family members , it could result in huge regret .
On top of that , it is better to think about solutions for a problem with family members , because there are more heads to think about it , rather than thinking about it alone and struggling on your own .
In the end , I believe that mental or even monetary support from her family could help the carrier to fight against the genetic disease .
It is true enough that there are lots of cancer patients who were given a second choice to live as a normal person because they had strong mental support from their loved ones .
In my opinion , as long as we keep our minds healthy and strong , we can fight any disease as it comes to us , when we are fragile and weak .
As the technology has advanced , it has reached a stage whereby the advancement triggers some ethical dilemmas in relation to the actual use of the technology .
Genetic testing has been made possible , making it easy to tell if one is a carrier of a known genetic risk .
If used for a good purpose , it could prevent unnecessary unhappiness ; however , it could also make a situation worse by revealing who the carrier is in the family .
The question given is whether a carrier of a known genetic risk should be obligated to tell his or her relatives . I think that the carrier should not be obligated to do so , because I believe that he or she has a right not to know .
Firstly , genetic testing is not something that is compulsory .
Of course , some people may do it to make their futures slightly happier ; however , the carrier , before the testing , can choose not to go for the test and simply live with the unknowns and accept the facts .
If he chooses to live with the uncertainty that the future holds and willingly accepts it , he could do that . This is something that has been 'normal ' to everyone in the past , since genetic testing was not possible .
It could be better for him or her this way .
Some people might say that it is a way to prevent giving birth to disabled children and causing them to suffer .
I personally think this is the right purpose of going through genetic testing , so that a family who can not afford to have a disabled child does not have to give birth to such a child and make the entire family suffer .
However , I believe that the carrier has the right not to be obligated to tell anyone , but has a responsibility to take action to prevent an ethical dilemma .
If the result turned out to be something that the carrier can not accept , then it would have been better not to know the truth .
I believe that even the carrier has the right not to know the actual facts .
After realizing the he or she is a carrier , the emotional damage may be hard to bear .
It could possibly cause a problem in a family and create more unhappiness in the family .
Overall , I believe that it entirely depends on the carrier to share the hard facts and face them with relatives , but still , he has no obligation to tell .
In fact , I strongly think that the carrier should weigh both the positive and negative consequences of taking the genetic test , and take an appropriate action given the results .
The emotional depression that the carrier might get , and the sense of guilt , can be expected , and could be a burden for the rest of his or her life .
On the other hand , without knowing about any genetic disorder and having to accept the fact of it , the family will stay positive and work together to overcome the disability .
I think the family will stay mentally healthy as it is , without having emotional stress .
It has been debated for years whether a carrier of a known genetic risk should be obligated to inform his or her relatives .
Any individual at risk for a disorder has the right to undergo genetic testing , but whether the results should be shared with others , especially close family members or relatives , is a topic that is worth discussing .
This is an issue that needs to be addressed because a family-related ethical dilemma is involved .
In this essay , a few arguments will be made in support of the view that a carrier of a known genetic risk should tell his or her relatives .
When we were born , each of us was surrounded by our families and relatives , with them welcoming us to this new world .
We were crying hard , but we were not alone ; our families and relatives raised us .
Hence , they should be the people that we are grateful for , and the people with whom we would like to share joy .
In a case pertaining to a health issue or serious disorder , it may seem that there is no point in sharing , but this involves more than just sharing of bad news .
One definitely has the right to disclose his or her health issues to anyone , but it 's also one 's responsibility to inform family and close relatives .
When a health issue is related to genetic risk , we focus on the word " genetic " , which highlights the risk of passing the disorder down to the next generation .
Therefore , I would argue that it is obligatory for a carrier of a known genetic risk to tell his or her relatives in order to avoid any family-related ethical dilemmas that could be raised in the future .
Regardless of the fact that one may argue that it 's up to the individual whether to disclose such health issues or to keep them private , it 's certainly helpful to share with close relatives for a proper discussion of solutions .
By doing so , one will feel less stressed in facing such a risk of a disorder .
Relatives will certainly be supportive and show more care towards the carrier of a known genetic risk .
By informing them , the carrier is never alone in fighting the battle of such a risk of disorder .
On top of that , because the genetic risk may pass down to the next generation , it will involve more than just one family .
Therefore , I would agree to the existence of an obligation to tell the relatives of both parties when one is about to get married and have children .
This would avoid the rise of more family-related ethical dilemmas .
There are also a number of more intangible advantages that could support the stance of informing the relatives of the results of the test .
In conclusion , in order to avoid a family-related ethical dilemma , it is best for any carrier of a known genetic risk to inform his or her relatives .
The benefits of doing so outweigh the disadvantages .
More support must be provided about whether to inform the relatives , in order to give better direction when one is standing at such a junction .
The decision to undergo genetic testing can only be made by the individual at risk for a disorder .
This is the common law in society .
However , it raises a new question : should a carrier of a known genetic risk be obligated to tell his or her relatives ?
This issue has been discussed for a long time .
However , there are still many points of view .
Here , we are going to identify the advantages and disadvantages of the issue .
Firstly , I believe most of us will agree with the following sentence : " I would be anxious about a family member who told me that he or she was a carrier of a known genetic risk " .
Frequently , the intention of a carrier who does not want to tell their family is to continue their own life without the anxiety of their family .
It is obvious that it will be better for one person to be worried than for many to be .
However , many of the carriers are not strong enough to overcome the challenges alone .
With the families ' support , there would be more energy to fight against this demon .
This demon is not easily defeated , and requires much energy and psychological support .
Families give you the courage and support that you can not retrieve by yourself .
That is the most essential element for overcoming the challenges .
Besides that , the risk of a known genetic disease is serious enough that it can not be described .
This seriousness can be larger than our imagination .
Lying in bed for the rest of our life , and even dying immediately — these are consequences which we can not imagine .
Families are the dearest things in our lives .
Without their concern and support , we would have a hard time continuing .
They play an important role in our lives which can not be replaced .
A known genetic risk can also critically affect the next generation .
Therefore , it is our responsibility to tell relatives in order to prevent undesired consequences .
Generally , the clinic or hospital will not tell the carrier 's families without the carrier 's agreement .
It is the ethic of hospital staff to keep secrets of all patients .
We can not blame them for being liable for the undesired consequences .
However , the hospital can provide a counselor to advise the carrier about actions that can be taken .
Therefore , this kind of circumstance will not occur again and again .
It is a method that benefits two parties , which is a win-win situation .
In conclusion , a carrier of a known genetic risk is encouraged to tell his or her relatives about the known genetic risk .
However , there may be some special cases that are hard to define .
Thus , advice from the hospital plays an important role .
The carrier is responsible for balancing his or her own interests and those of the family and even society .
It is a hard decision to make , but the most appropriate choice will create great circumstances for the carrier and his or her family in the future .
Given the risk of having a genetic disorder , many individuals have made the decision to undergo genetic testing .
Each individual that is diagnosed as a genetic risk carrier faces an ethical problem : they can choose to warn their relatives about their risk of being a carrier of the same genetic risk .
Or , they can choose to keep silent .
From my point of view , a carrier of a known genetic risk should not be obligated to tell his or her relatives , for the following reasons .
First of all , from the perspective of human rights , a genetic risk carrier should not be obligated to tell the truth to others .
This diagnosis can be regarded as a privacy issue .
They may not want this fact to negatively influence their life ; instead , they may want to keep it secret , keeping others from knowing about it .
This is reasonable since the exposure of the truth of being a carrier may cause them to be discriminated against .
Second , the relatives of the carrier can also choose to have their own genetic testing done , regardless of the diagnosis of the carrier .
When people want to check whether they are genetic risk carriers , they can consult their own doctor about it .
If they do not want to think about it too much , and view the whole issue as a bother , they may just ignore the possibility .
However , if a diagnosed carrier is obligated to tell his or her relatives , the relatives will be forced to learn about their own increased chances of being genetic risk carriers .
They will then be forced to accept the truth m which may make their subsequent lives miserable .
Many people may argue that fulfilling this obligation may result in saving the lives of a carrier 's relatives , because of the larger opportunity provided with an earlier diagnosis .
However , this is not exactly true when other factors are taken into consideration , including psychological and social effects .
If one such relative is told that he or she may have a higher risk of getting sick , he or she may be scared of the unknown ; partners , colleagues , or a spouse may choose to leave them , and many other situations may occur , ruining that relative 's life .
On the other hand , as stated above , a person who is prepared to face the result can individually choose to undergo the genetic testing .
In summary , a carrier of a known genetic risk should make their own decision about whether to tell their relatives .
This should be accepted from the positions of human rights , the freedom of acceptance of relatives , and for many other social reasons .
Making it into an obligation will restrict the choice of carriers and will bring a lot of confusion to their relatives .
A person 's knowledge that he or she is a carrier of a genetic disorder causes a greater dilemma than getting the disorder .
I agree that a carrier of a known genetic risk is obligated to tell his or her relatives .
There are four reasons why people do n't have to be shy about sharing their problems regarding a genetic disorder .
Firstly , the carrier and his or her family can take precautions ; physically , by taking action to reduce the chance of it being passed to offspring , and mentally , should that action fail to prevent it from being inherited .
Many syndromes such as Down 's Syndrome and Taylor Syndrome can be prevented if the mother takes proper medication and does n't consume harmful goods during pregnancy .
This information may not be known to the mother if she does n't tell her relatives about her condition .
If more people that know about her problem , there will be more channels to receive information .
If all efforts have been made and the children still suffer from the syndrome , then the family has to accept this fact and do whatever they can to bring about a good environment for their children 's growth .
This would not be the parent 's fault , because there is always a chance of the gene being inherited .
So , they have to also prepare mentally .
Secondly , treatment and medication for genetic diseases cost a lot .
Albinism is one example .
People with albinism have sensitive skin , and need regular treatment .
Unlike people with a high proportion of skin pigment , people with albinism are prone to sunburn and other skin diseases .
If they do n't treat their body well , such as by using sunglasses or wearing sunscreen outdoors , the chances are good that they will get skin problems that may also lead to cancer .
When you suffer from cancer , the cost for medication is very expensive .
To prevent the bigger problem from happening , it takes a lot of effort in taking care of your body .
If the carrier does n't tell his or her relatives , it may be too late to get their support and prepare financially .
Thirdly , some diseases are not noticeable and may lead to serious health problems .
One such disease is sickle cell trait .
Usually people are not aware if they carry the sickle cell gene and this may lead to circulatory problems such as blood blocking .
If the parents know that one of them is a carrier and disclose that information to their relatives , they can bring their children to undergo genetic testing , and do n't need to be ashamed about it , because it is for the sake of their children 's health .
Fourthly , it is important for the parents to provide a mental boost for their children with a genetic disorder .
When their children become teenagers , many social problems may arise .
People , including friends , often mock you for your conditions .
A strong mental condition and conviction must be built from within , with the help of the closest ones .
If not their family , then who else is there that is willing to do that ?
It is not a heavy job for the family if they have prepared mentally first by disclosing the information of the probability that their children may suffer from the genetic disorder .
In this modern world , technologies have improved a lot compared with last century .
Particularly , in the medical field , there has been a great improvement in many treatments for many formerly incurable diseases , and genetic testing is one of the methods which have been used to diagnose an individual at risk for a genetic disorder .
The medical authorities claimed that only the individual who is at risk for a genetic disorder can make the decision to undergo genetic testing .
However , once a test has been conducted and the results are known , a family-related ethical dilemma is born .
The question is whether a carrier of a known genetic risk should tell his or her relatives .
In my opinion , the carrier of a known genetic risk has to tell his or her relatives about this .
This is because his or her relatives have the right to know .
As many people realize , a genetic disorder can be related to the carrier 's relatives ; that is , one of the family members being at risk for a genetic disorder means that other family members also have almost the same risk of having it , so this problem should be treated seriously by the family .
Every family member has their human right to know what is going on with them .
If they do not even know that they are at risk for a genetic disorder , how can they have their right ?
For instance , John is informed by his doctor that he is at risk for a genetic disorder , but he does not tell his sibling , James , about this .
Although telling James about this is horrible to some extent , he should know what will be likely to be going on for him .
This might be beneficial for his future if he is aware of the risk of having this disorder .
The next point is that telling relatives can raise their awareness of having the same genetic disorder , preventing certain genetic disorders from affecting them .
Genetic disorders are innate , but the great improvement of medical treatment makes it possible for humans to prevent the disorder or to reduce the negative effects of the disorder for themselves .
In addition , doctors usually quote a statement , " Prevention is better than cure " ; this gives us the idea that preventing a disorder from happening has far more advantages than curing it .
Awareness of having a genetic risk may help in diagnosing a genetic disorder for a person , and therefore , this may make the prevention of a certain disorder possible .
For example , hypertension is partially due to genetic factors , but environmental factors also play an important role .
People who are aware of having such a disorder can prevent the disorder from happening by adopting a healthy lifestyle , including having a balanced diet and exercising for at least 30 minutes every day .
To sum up , a carrier of a known genetic risk should be obligated to tell his or her relatives .
It is their human right to know about it , and it may also save their lives by preventing the disorder from happening .
Together with the advancement of technology over the past decades , medical advancement has increased exponentially and further enhancements are still constantly continuing . Empowered with advanced medical knowledge , doctors are able to diagnose and undertake genetic testing for patients to help them prevent and take necessary steps to protect their lives . However , once a test has been conducted and the results are known , the question of whether to disclose the results to his or her relatives becomes a challenging issue to both patient and doctor . I feel a strong urge in support of the obligation to inform a patient 's relatives .
As it is a genetic risk , the patient 's next-of-kin might have a high chance of carrying the risk , and hence the need to inform their relatives is important so that necessary prevention actions could be taken before unforeseen circumstances might occur . For example , if you are the only child in a family and you are suffering from a genetic disease , such that the genetic trait might be passed on to the next generation if you have a child , letting your family members be aware of the situation would lessen family stresses from them forcing you to settle down and have children . However , social ethical issues like discrimination and privacy are the biggest concerns and potential barriers to enforcing patients or doctors disclosing information to patient s ' relatives . It challenges confidentiality and privacy principles . Currently , under the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 ( HIPAA ) in the United States , there is no legal obligation to disclose information to relatives ; instead , it is up to the patient to disclose to their family members . Early disclosure to family members brings about positive reactions and prevention , as in the case of Angelina Jolie , who chose to disclose information and underwent treatment to reduce the risk of breast cancer significantly ( to under five percent ) . I still can recall her reason for disclosing her own story , which was that she did not want to live under the shadow of cancer .
However , there are still people against the decision of revealing private information . As in the case of Alzheimer patients , it is up to the patient whether to disclose information . However , research has shown that doctors have tried to interpret who , how , and whom the Alzheimer disease will be disclosed , in order to minimise the potential negative impact to family members ( Dementia Today , 2012 ) .There are associations that provide help to Alzheimer patients , like the Alzheimer 's Association ( Alzheimer 's Association , 1980 ) . Although there are still thousands of genetic risk diseases out there that might not be receiving help and support from everyone , the need to receive immediate understanding and support from family members is a basic form of help that patients need during their difficult time .
In conclusion , the state should have passed a legal bill to provide information to doctors that determine to what extent a doctor should opt to reveal to relatives the genetic disease , and in which situations it is open to the patient 's decision . In addition , the state could also encourage the creation of assistance schemes to provide necessary help to needy patients to encourage them to open up for their own benefit and that of their family members . Although they may face challenges from social and ethical issues , in the long term , with appropriate encouragement and aid from the government , more individuals would have a different view of acceptance , and would take appropriate measurements to protect their own health and that of their loved ones .
Nowadays , study in genetics has gone further and further due to high-velocity technological advancement .
Not long ago , the human genome project sponsored by several large multinational corporations was started .
In comparison , in the field of genetic testing ( which enables people to be aware of the risk of a possible genetic disorder ) , where the technology has long been very mature , an even more popular topic arises .
While most people agree that each individual has his own right to decide whether to undergo a genetic test or not , they have different views one whether it is the patient 's responsibility or freedom to share the result with his or her relatives .
In my opinion , patients who are carriers of some known genetic risk are supposed to share the truth with their family members .
Admittedly , it is a social obligation to be responsible for the lives of other people .
For all of society , it is a duty .
Take H1N1 as an example ; all the people in Singapore , including students at school , travelers at the Changi Airport , workers in the office , and passengers on the street are forced by law to take their temperature and report the result to the relevant government authority in charge .
To those family members who care about them , it is also a moral obligation .
How can they not tell their loved ones who they really are , and thereby put their loved ones in danger ?
The basis of a family is that everyone trusts and loves each other with no doubts .
Without trust and love , there is no difference between a family and a bunch of strangers living together .
Hence , it is essential to tell their family members about the risk of their genetic disorder , both as a social responsibility , and as a favor to preserve the family .
Moreover , telling their family members the truth is the fastest and easiest way to get their support .
Without the support of loved ones , a patient 's life is no better than death .
Family members , as one of the closest groups of people from whom they can get comfort , are a crucial factor for them to successfully get over any possible troubles resulting from a genetic disorder .
A study of New York University in 2010 showed that patients with family members nearby generally recovered 2–4 days faster than those taken care of by professional nurses .
Even for those patients with terminal diseases , the duration of their survival is 30 % longer due to family support .
Some people may say that telling the truth may raise some unnecessary doubts and panics which will endanger family harmony .
While every family needs to go through occasional troublesome situations , the more troubles that a family has gone through together , the greater the bond that will be established between the family members as well as the greater amount of trust , love , and understanding .
Hence , for a family in which every member is truly believing in each other and loving each other , all these troubles are just tests to make them stronger .
As in the lyrics of Kelly Clarkson , what does n't kill you make you stronger .
Being in an Asian society where genetic testing is not a common practice , I do think that it is the choice of the patient whether he or she wants to tell his or her relatives about his or her disease .
Having the courage to take the genetic test and then to inform their relatives about the risk that they may have , may result in people being judgmental , even while it is actually just a risk , and not a confirmed case .
Furthermore , since it is the person 's genes that are affected , he has the right to determine with whom he wants to share the information .
Nevertheless , while I feel that a carrier should not be obligated to tell his or her relatives about the genetic risk , I would like to suggest that the person at least share the information with his or her potential partner ( husband or wife ) , since the individual 's genetic risk may affect their future children .
Many people in our society are not well informed about many genetic diseases , and many of them will be likely to judge , or at least to differentiate those who have genetic diseases , since they feel that the patients are abnormal or ' weird ' .
This is because many relate genetic diseases to those such as Bubble-Boy disease , autism , or Down 's syndrome .
Many who are affected with those diseases have different physical characteristics compared to those without the genetic diseases .
While we do know that we should not discriminate against them based on their limitations , many people still do it , with or without them realizing it .
In this particular case , we are discussing whether a person should tell his relatives about him having a RISK of a particular genetic disease .
It is normal for people to demand for a fair and similar treatment to what others receive , and therefore it is normal for people to try to keep some of their secrets or personal issues to themselves , in case some people judge them or treat them differently . Many people really love to hear what they want to hear , and therefore may just ignore the word ' risk ' and assume that the person has suffered from the disease .
To prevent that from happening , I do feel that it is up to the person whether he wants to share the information with his family since his family may either be paranoid or judge him and act differently .
Especially when it is just a risk , the option is really his , since he is not an actual sufferer .
There may be some people who say that it is necessary to tell the family members about the risk since some of them may be affected ; while I do think that this view has a point , how much you can trust your family regarding this issue may also be something to consider .
Maybe we can trust our immediate family members , but can we really trust all the other relatives ?
Furthermore , since the genetic risk or genetic disease is a very personal issue , it is up to the person to tell the relatives about it .
However , as I wrote earlier , it is better for the person to share the potential risk at least with his or her partner , since his genetic risk may later affect his children .
This information needs to be at least acknowledged by the other party before they make the decision to get married and have children .
There may be situations when both the husband and wife are carriers , in which case they should not have any children , since their children may not be able to survive after they are born .
Or , in a less extreme case , the child may be disabled .
This piece of information does play a role in family planning matters ; therefore , although no one is obliged to tell about their genetic risk to anyone , it should be encouraged for them to tell it to their future partner .
In conclusion , whether or not the carrier wants to tell his relatives regarding his genetic risk , the choice is his , because it is his own gene and he has the full rights to it .
He may have considerations beyond worry of being judged , and sharing may result in making his family worry for nothing ; no matter what choice he makes , we need to respect it , and we have no right in saying that he must tell his relatives about it .
We all know that life is priceless and that we have no right to judge a person 's death .
With improvements in technology , a new life possessing a genetic risk can be detected .
Genetic risk refers to the chance of inheriting a disorder or disease .
As such , an entirely new dilemma is born : should a carrier of a known genetic risk be obligated to tell his or her relatives ?
This essay will discuss the reasons why the relatives are obligated to be informed that their children have a genetic risk .
One of the reasons that the parents should be informed is that they have to decide whether they are capable of raising a child with a genetic risk .
A child with a genetic risk may not have the ability to work and build a family with others , and most of the time , they are not accepted by the majority .
They may not be able to enjoy the kind of life normal people can enjoy .
This competitive world is cruel to those who are not able to survive .
Parents and relatives have to work longer than expected to endlessly foster their child if he or she is not able to foster him- or herself .
The situation may become worse if the child has diseases like cancer or heart disease , which means that the parents have more heavy baggage called " medication fees '' .
Not only the child , but also the entirely family , will suffer .
It is still early for parents to decide whether they can care for a new life that is not able to work and may suffer pain his entire life .
The other reason that parents should know whether the baby they have is a carrier of genetic risk is for a nation 's good .
There are always newspaper reports that a newborn baby has been abandoned at a hospital , after the parents realized the baby has diseases that need a huge amount of money to treat .
Countries like Singapore are short of manpower to contribute to the nation .
Every year the government has to spend a lot to help the disabled with medical subsidies and special schools to educate them .
Without increasing number of disabled people in a nation , the government is able to concentrate development in other ways , like military and education .
As citizens of a nation , they have the responsibility to support their country in many ways .
Moreover , in the world we are living in today , many abortions are conducted in hospitals every day .
It is easier for people to accept it morally .
Therefore , I believe parents have the right to know the health of their child .
Many people may object to the theory that all people have the right to enjoy the world , particularly religious people .
However , the problem is , will people really enjoy their lives if they have to stay in a hospital every day , with all the needles and endless pain ?
Parents know what is best for their children ; thus , they will make the right decision after they have been informed .
Also , humans should improve the medical field in order to prevent this tragedy from happening .
I think a carrier of a known genetic risk should not be obligated to tell his or her relatives .
Genetic testing is a personal choice .
One should have full control of his or her information and it is his or her right to decide whether or not to disclose it to someone else .
As far as I am concerned , when a couple is going to have babies , they are going to run a few tests and see whether there could be some genetic diseases .
The results are disclosed to the husband and the wife .
This is not the case I am talking about here .
The most obvious reason for those who argue for this opinion is that the relatives of the carrier are at high risk of carrying these diseases .
They have the right to know whether they are at risk .
Also , telling them the result can let them largely reduce the cost for multiple testing .
They can also take immediate measures to reduce the possibility of having this disease .
If a person has a disease C that might be a result of gene A , he runs a test and knows that he has the gene AA .
he runs a test and know that he has the gene AA .
This means both of his parents have gene A , and they are both at high risk of having disease C. They could save the cost of running two separate tests to see whether they are at high risk of having disease C. If he runs a test and knows that he has the gene Aa , this means that one of his parents has gene A and the cost of one testing could be saved .
this means that one of his parents has gene A and the cost of one testing could be saved .
His relatives can then take measures , if this disease can somehow be prevented , to stop this disease from taking their lives .
However , this can also be achieved from personal choice .
One can choose to tell one 's relatives if they are at risk .
Most people care about their relatives ; if there is no serious consequence of telling them , I assume most of them will tell their relatives to be careful .
One might also choose to hint or encourage their certain relatives to run a gene test , if they are concerned about negative consequences that come up when they disclose their genetic results .
There are possible negative consequences that people might face if they disclose their genetic results to their relatives .
If a person is obliged to tell his or her relatives , he or she might be discriminated against by those who do not carry this gene .
He or she might even be advised not to get married or have children .
For example , if an unmarried person has gene Aa and gene aa is sufficient for a very serious disease , then
after he takes the test and is obliged to tell his relatives , everyone would know that he is a carrier .
If all the married couples go run a test and learn they are not carriers , they might subconsciously see him as different and worry that he will find a wife who will carry this gene as well .
Third , it is hard to define relatives .
If a gene runs in a family , and one of the family members tests positive , whom does he need to tell ?
If that is a big family , is he obliged to tell everyone ?
Spouses usually have very close relationships . If person tells his family that he has this gene , his uncle may tell his wife that he needs to run a test because his nephew has the disease .
However , the wife is not at risk of having this disease .
Then the wife might tell her mother , who likes to gossip on her way to the theatre .
In less than a week , half of the town knows that this person has a genetic risk , and that his entire family might be at risk .
Then nobody wants to marry that person , or his relatives .
This is the potential consequence if one does not have full control of his information , especially when the party that he is obliged to disclose his information to is a potentially large group ( such as relatives ) .
In conclusion , a carrier of a known genetic risk should not be obligated to tell his or her relatives .
Carriers of known genetic risks should be obligated to tell their relatives .
Nowadays , people not only pursue happiness in their own lives , but also a better future for the next generation .
Since modern technology is so advanced , people can decide to undergo genetic testing to find out whether they carry genetic risks that could affect the next generation .
The ethical dilemma is whether people should be responsible for telling their relatives if they carry a known genetic risk .
In my opinion , it is quite obvious that there is a responsibility to tell family and relatives .
There are two basic reasons .
First , it is important to be responsible for your well-being and the health of your relatives . The second one is being responsible for future generations .
Informing your relatives and families about your genetic risk is good for your well-being and health of your relatives .
If you are carrying a genetic risk , then there is a large possibility that your relatives , like parents or siblings , are also carrying the same genetic risk .
The genetic risk that you carry may or may not affect your health and put you in danger .
If you have n't undergone genetic testing , luck and fate dictate what will happen to you and your relatives .
However , if you have undergone testing and know that you are a carrier , you owe a responsibility to your whole family .
Even though you can not eliminate the risk completely , you can at least try to avoid developing the disease .
As for your family members who are more likely to be affected , they can go to the hospital for regular checkups .
Therefore , it is your responsibility to tell your relatives to get prepared to fight the disease and take steps to prevent it .
Furthermore , by telling the truth that you are carrying a genetic risk , you are also being responsible to future generations .
If your wife is not aware of the truth and gives birth to a baby , it is possible that your child will also be a carrier of the same genetic risk .
As a parent , you would not be acting responsibly to your progeny , since you would have allowed the genetic risk to be passed down from generation to generation .
However , if you tell the truth to your wife and relatives , you let them make an informed choice about whether to have a child or not .
And if you still decided to have a baby , since technology is advancing so rapidly , it is possible that the practice of altering genes would be perfected and widely used in the future .Then , you could choose to have babies and give them a brighter future .
This is the responsibility of being a parent .
In my opinion , this seems to be the main purpose of undergoing genetic testing in the first place .
In conclusion , once you have undergone genetic testing and are aware of carrying some specific genetic risk , you have responsibilities to your relatives , yourself , and your progeny to tell your family the truth .
To tell or not to tell
Imagine this : you decided to undergo genetic testing and learned the result .
You found out that you actually were a genetic risk carrier .
Then it became worrisome about whether you needed to tell your relatives , who might carry this genetic risk as well .
There are many things you need to consider .
This choice may have a huge impact on their lives .
What should you do ?
Tell them or keep this secret until you die ?
Many people feel that we should tell our relatives since we really care about their health .
For example , diabetes is a kind of genetic disease .
If we learned that we were carrying this genetic risk , it would be best for us to tell our family members because they might carry it as well .
If we told them , they might start paying more attention to their daily habits , like eating less sugary food .
It is especially important for young people to know .
The earlier we tell them , the better habits they can learn , which will be better for the rest of their lives .
What 's more , they may also undergo genetic testing to see whether they are carrying it or not , which is also better for them .
However , some people may argue , why would we want to interfere with their lives ?
Sometimes it is extremely hard for them to accept this news , especially if they learn that they or their descendants may have a severe disease like an untreatable blood disease .
Imagine that you are living a normal life but suddenly one day your relative comes and tells you that actually there is some possibility that you may develop some disease in the future . How are you going to feel ?
It may affect your daily life and you would think about it every day .
You would become so anxious that you could not focus on anything .
At the same time , there is also a chance that the genetic test results are not correct , which means that our relatives would be wasting their lives worrying about this untruth and we would actually have brought more trouble to them .
Personally I feel that we still should own our responsibility to tell them the situation .
Since this will really affect their lives , we should try to handle it positively .
We can not let it go .
We should know that although we may affect their lives , we can still let them make correct choices in the future .
It is only after we tell them will that they start paying attention to their health .
They will consider whether to have a baby because of this genetic problem and they will start finding ways to try to prevent their baby from also carrying this genetic risk .
They also have a choice about whether to undergo the genetic test or not themselves .
Maybe after we tell them , they will go for it and learn more about themselves .
Even though it will have a huge impact on their lives , we should recognize that we need to tell them and help them , because they are our loved ones .
A genetic risk carrier should be obliged to tell
Genetic testing is conducted when an individual is at risk of some possible disease .
Once the test is done , whether the results should be open to his or her relatives has caused extensive controversy .
Some say it is an invasion of the carrier 's privacy and this information should be protected .
He or she has the right not to tell anyone .
However , in my opinion , it is the obligation of a knowing genetic risk carrier to tell their relatives about their situation .
This essay will illustrate two aspects of this stance .
First of all , it can be a warning to the patient 's family members to be aware of the disease that they may have .
As we all know , genetic risk carriers are likely to share genes with their family members .
Once one person in the family is found to be carrying a genetic risk , other members in his or her family may also be at risk .
Some diseases may not show symptoms until the carrier reaches a certain age .
Therefore , telling relatives about the situation may avoid a lot of trouble in the future and give them time for proper treatment .
Sometimes lives may even be saved if they are told early enough to conduct timely treatment .
In consideration of the other family members , relatives should be informed .
Secondly , telling relatives can prevent genetic disease from being passed to the next generation .
Carriers should let their spouses know about their situation before marriage .
They need to ask for a doctor 's advice before they plan to have a baby .
Some genes will only be passed down to boys rather than girls , some are the opposite .
If a carrier refuses to tell the truth to his or her spouse , another life may be at risk of inheriting a genetic disease .
Some years ago , I read a true story in the newspaper .
A couple in China had a five year old son .
Their son unfortunately fell ill and he was diagnosed with a kind of genetic disease that was very serious .
They were told that the wife 's family was carrying the polygenetic disorder and it could only be passed down to boys rather than girls .
Therefore their son inherited the genetic disease .
The wife had known about the polygenetic disorder before getting married and she did not tell her husband .
The son died after one year 's treatment and after that the couple got divorced .
If the wife had not hidden the truth and asked for the doctor 's advice before they had the baby , this tragedy would have been prevented .
In a nutshell , the carrier of a known genetic risk has the responsibility to tell their relatives .
On the one hand , informing relatives will let the carrier 's family members know about the diseases they may have so that they can perform treatment in time , if possible .
On the other hand , hiding the truth may allow the disease to be passed to the next generation .
Nowadays , with the advancement of technology , it is easy to do genetic testing .
We can not deny that genetic testing helps people a lot when they face the prospect of disorders .
However , I think that genetic information is a person 's private matter , which should be protected by the law .
Therefore , I believe a carrier of a known genetic risk should not be obligated to tell their family .
There are three reasons , as follows .
First , genetic information is personal and should also be private , like a bank card PIN .
Other people should not be told without the person 's permission even if they are related .
The government should make a law to protect this kind of privacy .
Once someone 's genetic information is told to other people ,
they may know about that person 's potentially disabling diseases .
They may develop a bias against this person and even abandon him or her .
Because people do not have the ability to choose their genes , they should not be thought badly of because of defective genes .
Therefore , I think that regardless of the genes or whether the genes match with their parents , that information should not be told to anyone , even that person 's family .
Secondly , the carrier of a known genetic risk may destroy the family peace and even destroy the relationship between children and adults .
Once their family members find out , they may not have a relationship with that person anymore .
However happy they were before , some barrier would appear which would gradually destroy the family .
The relationship between parents and their children should not be tested based on genetics ; it is something much deeper and tighter .
The parents give knowledge and love to their children and feel happy with their children 's company .
Children rely on their parents to live .
When they grow up , they take care of their elderly parents to thank them for their dedication .
The relationship between parents and children is based on love and dedication .
No one wants to see a broken family because of a genetic risk carrier .
Therefore , I think carriers of a known genetic risk should not be obligated to tell their family .
Finally , the technology of genetic testing is still not very mature yet .
There is a chance of false results .
If a false result was found by the doctor , the family and children may be sad and struggle for their whole lives .
Therefore I think the carrier of a known genetic risk should not be obligated to tell his or her family and relatives .
Considering the people 's privacy and the existence of false results , for the peace of the family , I support that genetic risk information should not be released to a carrier 's family without that person 's permission .
Carriers of a Known Genetic Risk Should be Obligated to Tell Their Relatives
With the development of the medical technology , more and more illness are discovered to have a genetic component .
People can discover whether they carry a diseased gene by undergoing a genetic test .
If there is no problem , that would be wonderful .
However , not everybody is so lucky to not carry any diseased genes .
Therefore , once people find that they carry the diseased genes , they should be responsible for telling their relatives , at least their immediate family members .
It may be awkward and embarrassing for a person to tell relatives that they are a carrier of a known genetic risk ,
but since they are all from the same family and the same forefather , they share some part of the same genes .
Therefore there is nothing to be shy about or be afraid of .
If a person tells their relatives that they carry a diseased gene , their relatives can go to the hospital to check whether they also carry the same gene .
Then , the relatives can prepare themselves to prevent the disease from occurring
and prevent the disease from being passed to their offspring .
If relatives carry that diseased gene , they can help and share their experience with that person and teach them how to communicate with others about the issue .
If they get married , they must tell their partner that they carry the diseased gene .
Then they can have a healthy baby with the help of the doctors .
Or else , if they hold back the genetic risk , they may have an unhealthy baby , potentially leading to the death of the baby or end of their marriage .
I saw a story on TV about
a couple that could not have a child for a long time . Their parents were anxious and asked them to go to the hospital to check for a problem .
After coming back from the hospital , the man told his parents that the problem was that he carried a diseased gene so that he could not ever have a baby .
The woman did not know the test result , but she overheard the discussion and decided to divorce her husband .
After getting the divorce certificate , the man showed her the test result , which said that the woman carried the diseased gene instead of the man .
At that time , the woman knew how much her husband loved her but she ruined her happiness .
Tears accomplished nothing .
People can not avoid carrying the diseased genes that they were born with .
However , they can prevent the diseased genes from being inherited by their children .
Telling their relatives that they have a risk of carrying the diseased gene can cause their family members to bond more closely and also avoid many risks and conflicts .
Genetic testing has become a beneficial way to protect individuals at risk for a genetic disorder .
However , a family-related ethical dilemma arises : is it right to tell a carrier 's family once the test has been conducted and the results are known ?
I am inclined to believe that their relatives have a right to know the result .
The answer is simply that everyone , especially one 's family , has the right to know the truth .
Though it is said that sharing the results of genetic testing involves emotional and social risks , while the potential negative impacts of the risk still exist , the consequence will be significant if other family members do not know the test results .
Then they would be unable to have a suitable method to protect themselves and make emotional preparations .
Take Angelina Jolie for example . She is famous but she still revealed the truth about her genetic risk for developing breast cancer .
Nothing is too bad if you know how to look at the bright side with hope .
People may feel angry , depressed , or even guilty about their results .
In some cases , there may be tension between a carrier and their family because the result is also related to the others ' risk .
However , I believe that this is a normal reaction to the situation .
In addition , though it is possible in some cases that the carrier and their family may undergo specific discrimination in employment and their social life , how can people face more dramatic tragedies , such as sickness or death , if they can not overcome this harsh situation ?
Life is hard but people can not blame it for being unfair .
It is just because they do not become strong enough to overcome the hard times .
Furthermore , living with a secret is not a good feeling . If the situations of other relatives worsen , the carrier would feel guilty and depressed .
Moreover , the truth can not be hidden forever and the longer it is kept secret , the more shocking and upsetting it will be when it is revealed .
As a result , it is in the interests of the carriers and their relatives to disclose the genetic testing result .
Last but not least , even though genetic testing is a personal matter , telling the result to one 's family can help them improve and develop understanding and sympathy for each other , as well as promote awareness of taking care of everyone 's health .
This plays an important role in the possibility that relatives can overcome the discrimination of society and anxiety about the risks .
In a nutshell , I believe that people should be obliged to tell their relatives about genetic testing results for the good of their health .
It can be very difficult for them but it is necessary for the carriers and their family .
Emotional preparations and the ways in which a carrier explains their genetic condition are important so that they can convey the correct information to their relatives and guide them to conduct a similar genetic testing , if necessary .
The Impact Of Social Media
Social media plays a vital important role in our lives today .
It is almost impossible for us to keep away from it .
I started getting involved with Facebook one year ago , when I had just arrived in Singapore .
Now , I have more than 500 friends on Facebook and I 'm buried under hundreds of updates every day .
We keep up with each other 's updates through social media .
For example , if we change our phone numbers , we no longer need to notify each friend individually .
Instead , we can write a post and tag our friends to inform them of this kind of change .
And if you are not on it , you will just get lost .
In certain aspects , social media has given us many conveniences .
It is becoming even more convenient than talking on the phone , since it is free .
We discuss everything we like and we have more personal space . Our friends also have more access to know what we are doing and what we like .
Also , we get a chance to talk to famous people , like celebrities , and learn more about their lives .
In China , a lot of government organizations have open blogs to communicate with people , like firefighters , police stations and so on .
Social media allows them to explain or inform people about what is going on .
Actually , lots of rescuing jobs are done with the help of social media , like looking for people who have gotten lost and so on .
With more convenient and personal communications , the relationship between the government and its people has largely improved .
What 's more , various cultures can be shown to us through social media .
We can learn more about news and culture through social media .
In this aspect , social media has shortened the distance between us .
However , since social media is so convenient , advanced and interesting , we have fewer chances and it less important to talk face to face .
Even when we gather together , more people find themselves with less to talk about than before and choose to dig through their social media feeds instead .
When we are far away from one another , social media makes it seem as if we were in front of each other ; sometimes when we are by each others ' sides , social media makes us seem further away .
This feeling makes people 's relationships less stable , secure and reliable than before .
Besides , there are more people sharing pictures of their yummy food or traveling experiences .
To some extent , this makes our life seem more luxurious .
For myself , I long to visit some places after seeing the beautiful pictures taken by my friends .
Sometimes I can not even sleep well because of the excitement .
Social media makes our lives move so fast that it leaves us less time to think about our lives .
Social media is becoming more important and we need to think more about how to make it serve us better .
Interpersonal skills , like any other skills , require practice .
Besides that , time is required to develop and adapt these skills .
The burgeoning of social media has definitely had its time but , like all good things , it is better in moderation .
Convenience and efficiency are two very important benefits of social media .
With millions of users connected at any one time , any information is readily available for their perusal .
This improves the connectivity between users .
For example , one is able to send notifications and other information over the web that we once needed to send in hardcopy , and the process takes seconds .
The recipient will then receive the information almost immediately , depending on the quality of the network .
This convenience can be perceived as happening almost in real time .
Next , communication is also greatly improved .
In the past , most communication was done by one of many methods including telegrams , snail mail and poor quality voice calls .
With the introduction of applications such as Skype and Facetime , everyone can put aside most of the olden days ' communication methods .
In addition to transmitting voices , a web camera can also be affixed to emulate a ' real ' interaction with expressions and gestures .
Communication would have taken a different turn without easily available social media .
However , it is a good practice not to intensively use social media all the time .
Intimate interaction greatly lacks in social media interactions , particularly physical touch .
Having to meet and interact to talk allows one to be closer to the listener .
It involves a level of dynamic interaction that is coordinated by the cerebral cortex of the brain .
Unlike social media , where most interaction is done with thinking and typing .
As a result , one does not train the skills necessary for proper interpersonal relations .
It is also entirely incorrect to fault social media alone for the lack of interpersonal skills .
Howard Garner studied different types of intelligence in people and stated that interpersonal intelligence is a type of skill on its own - some have it , some do not .
Howard Garner mentioned that the different types of intelligence could be charted , by using tests , and ranked .
Fundamentally , those who scored a lower ranking for interpersonal skills were more likely to stumble when these skills were needed .
Even though social media is not necessarily bad , it must be used appropriately , whether for work , family , or friends .
The type of use must also be noticed : informing , interacting , discussion , or something else .
The amount of physical space separating the parties must also be considered .
For people who live very far from one another , intensive use of social media is justified .
Those who live within the same community should at least try to meet up and not use social media as their primary source of communication .
At the same time , social media improves interpersonal skills through dynamic interactions between individuals in real time .
The addition of physical presence and touch could build a better rapport between people interacting through social media .
Recently , the rise of social media has helped people to have closer connections with each other . It is a more convenient and cheaper way to be in touch compared with face-to-face meetings .
In my opinion , social media websites such as Twitter and Facebook will not affect the chance for people to have face-to-face contact and thus negatively affects interpersonal skills .
On the other hand , it may even increase the chance of having face-to-face contact with other people .
First of all , social media networks have large user bases , and they help link people from different parts of the world .
In the days before social networks , people might not have had the chance to meet others from different countries .
The people that they knew might have been limited to only the people they met in their daily life , like classmates and coworkers .
Therefore , social networks bring more and more connections between people and gives them a chance to chat with people they did not know before . This helps develop their interpersonal skills .
Secondly , even though social networks allow people to chat online but not face to face , they may still decide to meet their online friends face to face in their daily life .
In this case , social networks help people to talk more frequently .
For example , if social networks did not exist , business people would need to meet each other face to face , which is time consuming . Even meeting about business that is not very important still wastes a lot of time in travel .
However , social networks let people meet and chat much more easily . They can even use video chat and create group chats to talk to multiple parties at the same time .
Nowadays , even some companies conduct online video interviews with their applicants as it saves time and money .
Social networks may also have some negative impacts on people .
The largest negative impact is that , because of social networks , some people start to use and rely on the internet every minute of every day .
They take too much time using online social networks and therefore do not have time to interact with people in their real lives .
It not only affects interpersonal skills , but it also bad for people 's health if they spend too much time on social media .
In addition , social networks can leak personal information to the public , as cyberspace is neither perfect nor safe . People may not effectively protect their privacy online and , sometimes , some people may use others ' personal information maliciously .
In conclusion , the insecure online environment and spending too much time online are the potential negative factors of using social networks .
However , social networks also provide people with a convenient communication platform , and it increases the frequency with which they meet each other in person .
They also help people develop their interpersonal skills through online chatting .
Overall , there are more benefits than there are costs .
The world is increasingly becoming flattened by all kinds of social network websites such as Facebook and Twitter .
Through social media , we can even know what a friend who lives thousands of miles away eats for lunch .
From some points of view , social media has many advantages by letting us communicate with friends more cheaply and conveniently than traditional methods .
However , its disadvantages can not be ignored when you consider it as a platform to show off or as a stage for cyber crime .
Social network sites provide us with many conveniences .
Without hanging out with friends or talking with them on the phone , we can know their latest news by scanning the websites .
It helps us know more about each other .
It can make people become closer as well .
For example , if you find out that your friend 's favourite singer is Justin Bieber through Facebook , you can give them Justin Bieber 's new album or a concert ticket as a birthday gift .
It would be very sweet and you two would surely become closer .
In addition , social network sites can help you keep in touch with friends living very far away .
When I was in Egypt , I made some friends from Canada .
Without Facebook , we may have lost contact with each other .
However , thanks to Facebook , I can still keep in touch with them and know what they are doing , as if we lived close to each other .
The disadvantages of social media are quite undeniable .
Research shows that people will unconsciously hide their real thoughts when they post something publicly .
This means that one can not know another 's true thoughts or personality by reading the things that they share on social media , which could be quite upsetting if they communicate in real life .
which could be quite upsetting if they communicate in real life .
In addition , with all the friendly people on social networks , one may neglect the people surrounding them and just communicate with their friends on Facebook .
It is common to see two people sitting next to each other , seldom talking to each other . Instead they just look at their cellphones .
According to research , this kind of behaviour is not good for people 's psychological health .
Cyber communication is quite different from face-to-face communication and people who depend on cyber communication too much will be unaccustomed to real-life communication .
Additionally , cyber relationships do not always work in real life .
With their only close friends online and not in real life , people are more likely to feel lonely because of the unfulfilled , physiological need to bond with others with all five senses .
With the competitiveness people feel to be the best one around , social networks have now become a place to show off .
Some people post pictures on social networks of their expensive things or the overseas destinations they have visited and get a feeling of satisfaction by doing so .
It is mentally unhealthy and it may cause people , especially teenagers , to become material .
Last but not least , all of the personal information on a person 's social network page makes it convenient for criminals to use this information to commit crimes .
Above all , social networking sites are a double-edged sword . People can only take benefit from them by avoiding the possible disadvantages , such as by putting less personal information on their Facebook pages .
The modes of communication have changed over the years , from letter writing to social networking .
This phenomenon is caused by rapidly changing technology , which has made communication faster than ever before .
Today , social media sites , such as Facebook and Twitter , are relatively common within contemporary society , and people can communicate with each other through these platforms .
They can even make new friends with similar interests and can connect with almost anyone in many parts of the world .
However , critics may argue that the existence of social media has reduced physical human interactions among people as they prefer sitting in front of a computer to going out and making new friends .
This essay will discuss both the benefits and downsides of using social media in contemporary society .
Nowadays , social media can disseminate information faster than any other form of media .
About 50 % of people learn about breaking news from social media .
This is due to people spending more time on social networks than reading newspapers .
Furthermore , with current technology , smartphones can access social media sites , making it even easier for consumers to use them .
Social media has benefited the masses by equipping them with a powerful tool to disseminate information almost immediately to the people around them .
However , critics may argue that not all information or news disseminated is reliable .
False information or hoaxes can also be spread on social media .
For example , in 2012 , false rumors of fires , shootouts , and caravans of gunmen in a Mexico City suburb spread through Twitter and Facebook .
This caused panic among the people , who flooded the local police department with numerous phone calls , resulting in the temporarily closing of schools .
The spread of false information can be a psychological threat to anyone given how quickly social media can disseminate information .
There are cyber police who roam around these social networking platforms to prevent these hoaxes from spreading .
Despite high security , there will still be unreliable sources spreading false information on social media sites to control almost every social-network movement .
Social media can improve relationships and facilitate making new friends , provided that there is mutual trust and mutual understanding between both parties .
Many teenagers today claim that they are able to keep in touch with their friends through social media , regardless of their location .
In the past , people used to write letters to their friends and it would take a relatively long time to deliver the letters .
With the help of technology , people can conveniently catch up with each other .
Furthermore , it is easier to make new friends who have similar interests or hobbies .
However , in order for people to maintain their current relationships as well as make new friends , there must be mutual trust and understanding .
It might not be accurate to judge another person 's feelings over social media since people can hide their true emotions online .
There is a chance that people may miscommunicate with each other as they can not sense one another 's tone over social media platforms , which will result in unnecessary conflicts .
which will result in unnecessary conflicts .
But , if there is trust and mutual understanding on social media , it will be ideal for people to improve their relationships and make new friends .
In conclusion , social media in contemporary society can help people improve their relationships and make new friends , as well as disseminate information efficiently to the masses .
However , there is a risk of false information and opportunities for miscommunication .
Nevertheless , the advantages of social media can be beneficial if the negative aspects of it can be carefully taken care of .
All-in-all , social media is the product of rapid technological advancement , more of which are to come in future .
Social media sites have greatly facilitated long-distance communication and interaction due to their accessibility and convenience .
In today 's globalised and interconnected world , Twitter and Facebook are now the mainstream platforms for social interactions .
With just a click on any electronic device , anyone can easily interact and communicate with their friends without much hassle .
Thus long-distance relationships and friendships can be easily maintained , and keeping in touch with your circle of friends has been made much easier .
People can engage with each other more easily through the sharing of personal photos , posting about their feelings or experiences , and the ability to reply to another 's posts .
Introverts or those who are too shy to communicate with their friends in person are now able to do so with words via social media platform .
In this way , socialisation can occur seamlessly and effectively through social media platforms . Meetups and appointments are no longer a barrier for humans to contact and communicate with one another , making human interaction possible at one 's own convenience .
Society will adapt to such phenomena as physical interaction is transformed into cyber interaction .
With the frequent use and reliance on social media and the Internet , a society that socialises online will become more advanced and adapted to a highly connected world .
This will greatly help society progress rapidly .
On the other hand , there are disadvantages to social media . One of the main concerns of using social media platforms to communicate is credibility .
The veracity of what is being shared or expressed can not be proven as media limits physical interactions , except when using a webcam to chat .
We can not be certain for sure of the truth of the posts or information we receive through the Internet .
We may actually be communicating with the hoax Facebook account of a cyber " friend " , which we assumed to be real but in reality is fake .
Photos and information retrieved from their profile page may be fabricated to suit certain personal agenda .
Thus , the lack of face-to-face human contact through social media restricts actual interactions which can be stimulated through the media .
Although emoticons can be used to show certain emotions , this differs from the authentic emotions you observe them your friends ' body language and facial expressions .
The danger of such communication is the uncertainty due to lack of physical interaction .
Furthermore , this lack of physical interaction has affected interpersonal behaviour since communication is made through social media instead of in-person meetings .
This reduces people 's experience interacting with one another which can adversely shape their behaviour .
The lack of exposure to real-life interactions will cause people to not build the confidence and skills needed to interact seamlessly and effectively with others .
Therefore , for an effective and efficient society , people need to have a balance between social media and face-to-face interactions .
Nowadays , people can use their phones to read the news and everyone can be the first witness of what is happening in the world .
People use Twitter to follow the artists or celebrities they love and Facebook to see their friends ' recent activity .
Nevertheless , they can still use their phones to make normal calls and messages to connect .
Not only did the phone do their jobs for them , but so do devices like personal computers , laptops , and tablets that can connect to the internet .
It is obvious to see that the internet saves people 's time and also connects people globally .
Several arguments have been made regarding the inevitable disadvantages social media may have for people .
People can only use electronic devices to access the internet .
Whenever they need to use social media , they have to use a phone or the internet .
Generally people need their eyes to look at the display of their phone or computer and their fingers to manipulate the device .
As a result , they will not have eyes to make contact with or hands to express their feelings to the people near them , which means that they have lost the tools they need for face-to-face communication .
This can be easily seen in restaurants or cafes nowadays .
A family of four is having dinner in a restaurant without any interaction because they 're holding and looking at their screen with one hand when the other hand is holding a fork .
A group of friends is having high tea in a café , also without chatting , because they do not know what to talk about , so they are touching their phone screens instead .
The children nowadays do not know what neighbourhood games are and who is standing beside them : all they know is how to press icons on screens .
These are some concrete examples of how social media reduces face-to-face human contact .
When people get used to using social media to contact other people , their interpersonal communicating skills will degrade and be lost eventually .
They have lost the courage to meet strangers , even the courage to talk .
Additionally , they will not have enough experience to communicate with people in person and not be trained in their conversation skills .
As a result , social media helps them do their jobs but indirectly affects their interpersonal skills .
Social media does have some other advantages .
First of all , people save money by using the internet to contact other people and read the news .
A father may be able to call his daughter in another country via social media instead of making international phone calls , which costs a lot to middle-class families .
He can even talk to his daughter face-to-face using video calls over the internet .
Secondly , people can make friends all over the world and can easily update their friends about their recent activities .
A guy who is going to travel for months can easily tell all of his friends about his activities .
When one of his friends who is not aware of this has failed to contact him via telephone calls , he might be able to find out his whereabouts using social media .
These are the advantages that save effort most of the time .
In conclusion , social media benefits people in several ways but , at the same time , harms people .
People should avoid the misuse of social media and use it in the proper way .
With the aid of social media , people bond globally , information flows rapidly , and humans live happily .
All of us are living in a technological society .
Have you ever wondered why we use these tools to connect with other people ?
It started with the invention of technology , which has evolved tremendously over the past few decades .
In the past , we traveled by ship but now we can use airplanes to do so .
In the past , it took a few days to receive messages as we need to post our letters but now we can use e-mail , which stands for electronic mail , to send messages to our friends or even use our cell phones to send messages .
From these examples , we can see that the physical distance between people and their loved ones is getting further apart .
This is because , with the ease of technological advancements such as the airplane , some of your friends might be going overseas to continue their studies or even you may go away from your family to pursue your studies or even careers .
Thus , this makes Twitter and Facebook become the media that we need to stay in touch .
However , everything in life has positive and negative effects .
This is also applicable to social media sites .
The next two paragraphs will discuss the advantages and disadvantages of using social media in our society .
With the help of social media tools , we can stay in contact and keep ourselves up to date with our family and friends even though we are away from them .
Social media sites such as Facebook allow us to share pictures or even chat online with our parents while we are overseas .
This helps parents communicate with their children and know what kind of activities they are doing while they are traveling .
Social media is beneficial since it connects you with your loved ones even though you are separated by distance .
It might not be able to replace the joy that you have when you are with your family , but it could help to reduce the sadness of being away from them .
